  <h1>What is Arm's Length Price?</h1>
  <div class="byline"><span class="av">SR</span><b>NumberIQ Glossary</b><span class="sep"></span><span>Last reviewed June 2026</span></div>
</header>
<div class="divide"></div>

<article class="prose read">
  <p class="answer-first lead"><b>The arm's length price (ALP) is the price that would be charged in a comparable transaction between unrelated parties under similar conditions.</b></p>
  <h2>How it works</h2>
  <p>It is determined using the most appropriate of the prescribed methods (CUP, RPM, CPM, PSM, TNMM or the other method), supported by a benchmarking study.</p>
  <div class="callout law"><b>Reference.</b> Section 92C; Rules 10B, 10CA.</div>
  <div class="faq"><h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>
    <details><summary>What is the arm's length price?</summary><p>The price unrelated parties would agree in a comparable transaction, used to test related-party pricing.</p></details>
    <details><summary>How is ALP determined?</summary><p>Using the most appropriate of the prescribed methods, with a benchmarking study and FAR analysis.</p></details>
  </div>
  <div class="key-takeaways"><h2>Key takeaways</h2><ul><li>ALP is the unrelated-party price benchmark.</li><li>Determined by the most appropriate method.</li><li>Supported by a benchmarking study.</li></ul></div>
  <div class="tools-cta" style="margin-top:22px"><b>Go deeper:</b> <a href="../insights/arm-length-price-methods-section-92c.html">ALP methods (92C)</a> </div>
